Brazilian Stock Movers: QGEP Participacoes, Pao de Acucar, Vale

-- B y   N e y   H a y a s h i
-- 
2011-07-05T20:28:15Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-05/brazilian-stock-movers-qgep-participacoes-pao-de-acucar-vale.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  Sao Paulo  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4:15 p.m. New York time.
Preferred shares are usually the most-traded class of stock.  The Bovespa Index fell 1.3 percent to 63,038.81.  Cia. Brasileira de Distribuicao Grupo Pao de Acucar (PCAR4
BS) tumbled 1.9 percent to 70.70 reais. Casino Guichard-
Perrachon SA told  Brazil ’s state-run development bank BNDES that
it will seek to keep a controlling stake in Pao de Acucar, O
Estado de S. Paulo reported, citing an unidentified Casino
official. BNDES said July 1 it will finance the merger between
Pao de Acucar and Carrefour SA’s Brazilian unit as long as
there’s a “friendly understanding” among all involved.  QGEP Participacoes SA (QGEP3 BS) gained 2.3 percent to 17
reais. The  oil company  owned by Queiroz Galvao SA said in a
regulatory filing it agreed to buy a 10 percent stake in oil
block BM-S-8 in Brazil from Royal Dutch Shell Plc.  Rossi Residencial SA (RSID3)  (RSID3 BS) slumped 4.6 percent to
12.56 reais. The company led declines by homebuilders after Bank
of America Corp. cut the sector to “equalweight” from
“overweight” on concern rising  interest rates  will affect
earnings. The  BM&FBovespa Real Estate (IMOBBV)  Index dropped 1.7 percent
to 887.47, the lowest in four months.  Tam SA (TAMM4)  (TAMM4 BS) jumped 4.6 percent to 36.46 reais. Shares
gained on speculation  Chile ’s antitrust tribunal will approve
Lan Airlines SA’s $4.1 billion takeover of its Brazilian rival.
Lan said July 1 that German regulators had approved the tie-up,
which made investors more optimistic on a favorable ruling in
Chile, according to Ignacio Spencer, who covers Lan for IM Trust
in Santiago.  Vale SA (VALE3)  (VALE5 BS) declined 1.5 percent to 46.33 reais.
Shares tumbled as concern mounted that interest rates may rise
again in  China , the company’s top export market. Separately,
Jinchuan Group Co. offered $1.3 billion for Metorex Ltd.,
topping a bid from Vale as the mining companies compete for
African copper assets.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ney Hayashi in Sao Paulo at 
 ncruz4@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Papadopoulos in New York at 
 papadopoulous@bloomberg.net  